WEBVTT

1
00:00:07.320 --> 00:00:09.600
- July 1942.

2
00:00:09.640 --> 00:00:12.200
It's been over a year
since Adolf Hitler

3
00:00:12.240 --> 00:00:16.200
launched Operation Barbarossa
against the Soviet Union.

4
00:00:16.239 --> 00:00:17.680
After initial success.

5
00:00:17.720 --> 00:00:21.120
the German campaign bogs down
across all fronts.

6
00:00:21.160 --> 00:00:25.080
so Hitler prepares
to launch another offensive.

7
00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:28.680
One of his objectives
is capturing Stalingrad.

8
00:00:28.720 --> 00:00:31.600
a city of great strategic
and symbolic value.

9
00:00:31.640 --> 00:00:36.120
particularly to the Soviet
leader. Joseph Stalin.

10
00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:42.120
One of the titanic battles of
World War II is about to erupt.

11
00:00:43.280 --> 00:00:45.400
- All wars change the world.

12
00:00:45.440 --> 00:00:47.000
But none of them
changed the world

13
00:00:47.040 --> 00:00:49.320
like the Second World War did.

14
00:00:49.360 --> 00:00:53.680
- Japan's on the march.
Germany's on the march.

15
00:00:53.720 --> 00:00:55.080
- No one can imagine

16
00:00:55.120 --> 00:00:57.520
the nightmare
they're about to unleash.

17
00:00:57.560 --> 00:01:00.280
The most destructive war
in human history.

18
00:01:00.320 --> 00:01:03.080
- Suddenly. the world
is turned upside down.

19
00:01:03.120 --> 00:01:04.519
and all hell is let loose.

20
00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:11.080
- The West is stunned
by the speed of the advance.

21
00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:14.160
- You get the Allies
led by the big three--

22
00:01:14.200 --> 00:01:16.960
Roosevelt. Churchill. Stalin.

23
00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:18.800
- Men who were dealing with

24
00:01:18.840 --> 00:01:21.960
immensely complicated
questions.

25
00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:26.520
- It's the biggest military
operation of human history.

26
00:01:26.520 --> 00:01:28.000
-The Allies have to
come together

27
00:01:28.040 --> 00:01:29.400
not just militarily.

28
00:01:29.520 --> 00:01:30.880
but industrial scale

29
00:01:31.040 --> 00:01:33.120
it's a global perspective.

30
00:01:33.320 --> 00:01:35.080
- They have to fight
in every climate

31
00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:38.520
from the Arctic
to the jungles of the Pacific

32
00:01:38.560 --> 00:01:42.120
to the deserts of Africa
and the depths of the ocean.

33
00:01:44.840 --> 00:01:47.680
- But there was
no certainty of victory.

34
00:01:47.720 --> 00:01:51.120
It was going to be
a horrific bloodbath.

35
00:01:51.160 --> 00:01:53.160
- We see humans
at their absolute worst.

36
00:01:53.200 --> 00:01:55.640
how they treat other
human beings.

37
00:01:55.680 --> 00:01:57.280
And we see them
at their absolute best.

38
00:01:57.320 --> 00:01:59.640
willing to give their lives
that others might live.

39
00:01:59.680 --> 00:02:02.680
- World War II was a struggle
in which there could be

40
00:02:02.720 --> 00:02:06.120
one victor and one vanquished.

41
00:02:37.120 --> 00:02:39.280
- June 1942.

42
00:02:39.320 --> 00:02:41.960
Adolf Hitler travels
to Finland to meet

43
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:45.920
with Finnish military leader
Carl Gustaf Mannerheim.

44
00:02:48.600 --> 00:02:50.280
The Germans are about
to launch

45
00:02:50.320 --> 00:02:54.040
another major offensive
against the Soviet Union.

46
00:02:54.080 --> 00:02:59.240
But to do so. the Wehrmacht
needs access to more oil.

47
00:03:11.320 --> 00:03:15.600
- Hitler's main supply of oil
is from his ally Romania.

48
00:03:15.640 --> 00:03:17.840
but he confesses to Mannerheim

49
00:03:17.880 --> 00:03:22.400
how dependent Germany is
on that one source of fuel.

50
00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:36.160
- Hitler's also concerned
the Romanian oil fields

51
00:03:36.200 --> 00:03:39.760
are vulnerable
to Allied air attacks.

52
00:03:42.640 --> 00:03:44.480
- Oil is always a problem
for Hitler.

53
00:03:44.520 --> 00:03:46.000
Unlike the United States
or Russia.

54
00:03:46.040 --> 00:03:48.800
Germany doesn't have
an internal source of oil

55
00:03:48.840 --> 00:03:50.360
or petroleum
that it can tap into.

56
00:03:50.400 --> 00:03:52.920
It must go get it
from somewhere else.

57
00:03:54.360 --> 00:03:56.280
- The Caucasus.
the mountainous region

58
00:03:56.320 --> 00:03:58.840
of the Soviet Union's
southwest.

59
00:03:58.880 --> 00:04:02.680
contains some of the richest
oil fields in the world.

60
00:04:02.720 --> 00:04:05.000
If the Germans can seize them.

61
00:04:05.040 --> 00:04:07.400
the Wehrmacht will have
all the oil it needs

62
00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:10.800
as well as depriving
the Soviets' access.

63
00:04:14.200 --> 00:04:16.800
- The Caucasus is
a vast mountain range

64
00:04:16.839 --> 00:04:20.399
that spans Europe and Asia
750 miles.

65
00:04:20.440 --> 00:04:22.560
This is going to be
a serious obstacle

66
00:04:22.600 --> 00:04:25.800
for any army that tries
to traverse it.

67
00:04:25.840 --> 00:04:28.120
- Hitler and his generals
prepare a plan

68
00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:33.120
to conquer the Caucasus:
Operation Blue.

69
00:04:33.160 --> 00:04:36.120
The southern army group first
head towards the Volga River

70
00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:38.560
to secure this
vital supply route

71
00:04:38.600 --> 00:04:42.760
and prevent the Soviets
from moving in reinforcements.

72
00:04:42.800 --> 00:04:46.000
Next. capture the fields.

73
00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:49.080
- Can they get there?

74
00:04:49.120 --> 00:04:50.880
If they could.
could they go ahead

75
00:04:50.920 --> 00:04:52.920
and pull all that oil
out of there?

76
00:04:52.960 --> 00:04:54.960
Do they have
the logistical means necessary

77
00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:57.760
to get it back to Germany?

78
00:04:57.800 --> 00:05:02.240
This is Hitler's idea.
It has to be successful.

79
00:05:04.760 --> 00:05:08.640
- Until now. Hitler's campaign
against the Soviet Union

80
00:05:08.680 --> 00:05:10.280
has proven to be
far more difficult

81
00:05:10.320 --> 00:05:13.320
than he and the German
High Command anticipated.

82
00:05:15.520 --> 00:05:19.480
- In June of 1941. the Germans
launched Operation Barbarossa.

83
00:05:19.520 --> 00:05:22.000
the invasion
of the Soviet Union.

84
00:05:22.040 --> 00:05:25.600
the biggest military operation
of all time.

85
00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:28.040
Hitler's banking
on a quick win.

86
00:05:28.080 --> 00:05:30.720
The Germans take tens
of thousands of square miles

87
00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:34.160
and capture millions
of Soviet soldiers.

88
00:05:34.200 --> 00:05:35.720
but they don't take Moscow.

89
00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:37.680
They don't get the quick win.

90
00:05:37.720 --> 00:05:40.440
The war goes on into 1942.

91
00:05:43.560 --> 00:05:45.560
- Barbarossa did not
meet its objectives

92
00:05:45.600 --> 00:05:46.880
set by Adolf Hitler.

93
00:05:46.920 --> 00:05:48.800
which was to capture
vast amounts of land.

94
00:05:48.840 --> 00:05:52.800
to get raw materials.
also to wreck Bolshevism.

95
00:05:52.840 --> 00:05:55.240
which needed the collapse
of the Soviet Union

96
00:05:55.280 --> 00:05:57.800
to happen rapidly.
none of which happened.

97
00:06:00.040 --> 00:06:02.080
- Hitler is concerned
he's gotten himself in trouble

98
00:06:02.120 --> 00:06:04.440
in the Soviet Union.
but he's convinced

99
00:06:04.480 --> 00:06:07.040
that the situation
can be righted.

100
00:06:07.080 --> 00:06:09.280
He can continue this war
forever

101
00:06:09.320 --> 00:06:13.160
as long as he has
a sufficient supply of oil.

102
00:06:13.200 --> 00:06:15.440
And that's what
the 1942 strike

103
00:06:15.480 --> 00:06:16.880
is going to take care of.

104
00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:19.920
a strike for the oil fields
of the Soviet Union.

105
00:06:19.960 --> 00:06:23.480
This is the world's first war
for oil.

106
00:06:27.680 --> 00:06:29.720
- June 1942.

107
00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:31.720
German forces begin
their push south

108
00:06:31.760 --> 00:06:34.280
towards the Volga as planned.

109
00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:37.600
- Hitler is impatient
and desperate

110
00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:41.160
to get the oil fields
as soon as he can.

111
00:06:43.520 --> 00:06:45.240
- But then he splits

112
00:06:45.280 --> 00:06:47.800
the southern army group
in two.

113
00:06:49.600 --> 00:06:52.760
- For Hitler. Operation Blue
is an exercise in frustration.

114
00:06:52.800 --> 00:06:54.440
The armies aren't
moving fast enough.

115
00:06:54.480 --> 00:06:56.280
they're not meeting
the objectives.

116
00:06:56.320 --> 00:06:57.640
And for that reason.

117
00:06:57.680 --> 00:07:00.160
he decides to split them
into two big groups.

118
00:07:03.160 --> 00:07:04.520
- It's a measure
of his arrogance

119
00:07:04.560 --> 00:07:05.960
that he thought
he was just simply

120
00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:08.360
going to be able
to divide this force.

121
00:07:08.400 --> 00:07:10.840
and in some
of the most difficult

122
00:07:10.880 --> 00:07:13.080
fighting terrain of Europe.

123
00:07:14.880 --> 00:07:17.200
- Hitler orders most
of the southern army group

124
00:07:17.240 --> 00:07:20.040
to push directly
for the oil fields.

125
00:07:20.080 --> 00:07:22.000
The job of seizing the Volga

126
00:07:22.040 --> 00:07:25.200
will now be left
to a single combat force.

127
00:07:25.240 --> 00:07:30.200
one of the biggest
and most experienced...

128
00:07:30.240 --> 00:07:34.240
the 6th Army.

129
00:07:34.280 --> 00:07:37.120
- The German 6th Army
is the largest army

130
00:07:37.160 --> 00:07:39.880
in the German order of battle.

131
00:07:39.920 --> 00:07:41.400
At the beginning
of the campaign.

132
00:07:41.440 --> 00:07:44.480
the 6th Army had
over 300.000 men in it.

133
00:07:46.360 --> 00:07:48.240
- By the middle of August.

134
00:07:48.280 --> 00:07:49.880
they're closing in
on the Volga

135
00:07:49.920 --> 00:07:53.360
and the city that guards it.
Stalingrad.

136
00:07:57.040 --> 00:08:00.720
- Stalingrad is named after
Adolf Hitler's personal rival

137
00:08:00.760 --> 00:08:04.320
and the personification
of Bolshevism. Joseph Stalin.

138
00:08:06.360 --> 00:08:08.480
- It's Stalin's city.

139
00:08:08.520 --> 00:08:11.000
It was named to commemorate
a great victory he won

140
00:08:11.040 --> 00:08:15.000
over the Whites
in the Russian Civil War.

141
00:08:15.040 --> 00:08:18.560
He doesn't want to surrender
a city named after himself.

142
00:08:20.440 --> 00:08:23.960
- Stalingrad itself is also
a major industrial center

143
00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:27.440
which produces something
like 20% of Soviet tanks.

144
00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:29.800
including the famous T-34.

145
00:08:29.840 --> 00:08:32.320
Along with a lot
of other products

146
00:08:32.360 --> 00:08:34.280
critical to the war economy.

147
00:08:34.320 --> 00:08:37.679
Stalingrad is a prize
in its own right.

148
00:08:39.360 --> 00:08:40.640
- Once again.

149
00:08:40.679 --> 00:08:42.559
the Red Army is
forced to retreat

150
00:08:42.600 --> 00:08:44.600
by the Wehrmacht.

151
00:08:46.560 --> 00:08:48.920
- The German forces
with their shirts off.

152
00:08:48.960 --> 00:08:50.400
It's summer.

153
00:08:50.440 --> 00:08:52.760
And they're just racing
across the steppes.

154
00:08:52.800 --> 00:08:55.400
and the Red Army
is just collapsing.

155
00:08:56.760 --> 00:08:58.120
- Stalin understands that

156
00:08:58.160 --> 00:09:00.400
if Hitler controls
the Volga River.

157
00:09:00.440 --> 00:09:02.920
that he will control
the supply lines.

158
00:09:02.960 --> 00:09:04.120
and therefore.
there's a chance

159
00:09:04.160 --> 00:09:06.840
he can defeat
the Soviet Red Army.

160
00:09:06.880 --> 00:09:11.920
- Stalin goes into
a free fall panic.

161
00:09:13.480 --> 00:09:15.080
- Stalin is determined

162
00:09:15.120 --> 00:09:19.600
that this is where Hitler
must finally be stopped.

163
00:09:19.640 --> 00:09:21.880
In late July 1942.

164
00:09:21.920 --> 00:09:25.680
as the German 6th Army
advances on Stalingrad.

165
00:09:25.720 --> 00:09:30.560
he issues a directive
from Moscow. Order 227.

166
00:09:32.280 --> 00:09:34.200
- As the Germans are advancing

167
00:09:34.240 --> 00:09:38.640
and getting ever closer
to Stalingrad in July 1942.

168
00:09:38.680 --> 00:09:40.800
Stalin issues Order 227.

169
00:09:40.840 --> 00:09:43.560
This is the so-called
Not a Step Back

170
00:09:43.600 --> 00:09:45.400
or Ni Shagu Nazad order.

171
00:09:45.440 --> 00:09:49.360
No more retreat
will be tolerated.

172
00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:50.800
- He's reading
a lot of Roman history

173
00:09:50.840 --> 00:09:52.240
about how the Roman army

174
00:09:52.280 --> 00:09:55.000
punished units
for surrendering.

175
00:09:55.040 --> 00:09:57.840
Stalin says.
we've lost too many provinces.

176
00:09:57.880 --> 00:10:00.360
We've lost all
of European Russia.

177
00:10:00.400 --> 00:10:02.480
The retreat must stop now.

178
00:10:02.520 --> 00:10:05.440
Not one more step back.

179
00:10:05.480 --> 00:10:08.440
Anyone who retreats
in any shape or form

180
00:10:08.480 --> 00:10:10.640
will be instantly executed.

181
00:10:14.120 --> 00:10:15.800
- There are going to be
blocking units

182
00:10:15.840 --> 00:10:20.040
made up of the secret police.
NKVD. commissars.

183
00:10:20.080 --> 00:10:21.920
people like that
whose job it is

184
00:10:21.960 --> 00:10:26.440
to kill soldiers that are
coming back towards them.

185
00:10:26.480 --> 00:10:30.760
- The reason Stalin gives this
order. however. is revealing.

186
00:10:30.800 --> 00:10:34.240
The Soviets were presumed
at the beginning of the war

187
00:10:34.280 --> 00:10:37.320
to have had these
vast and almost endless

188
00:10:37.360 --> 00:10:41.240
stores of manpower. of grain.
of wheat.

189
00:10:41.280 --> 00:10:42.640
a big country. after all.

190
00:10:42.680 --> 00:10:46.360
a much bigger country
than Nazi Germany.

191
00:10:46.400 --> 00:10:49.840
But as many as 70 million
former Soviet subjects

192
00:10:49.880 --> 00:10:53.000
are now behind German lines.

193
00:10:53.040 --> 00:10:54.600
And we shouldn't forget.
of course.

194
00:10:54.640 --> 00:10:56.840
that Nazi Germany is now
drawing on the resources

195
00:10:56.880 --> 00:10:58.680
of occupied Europe as well.

196
00:10:58.720 --> 00:11:03.120
And in Stalin's calculations.
Stalin no longer thinks

197
00:11:03.160 --> 00:11:06.240
the Soviets have
a manpower advantage.

198
00:11:06.280 --> 00:11:09.160
So the essence of this order.
Not a Step Back.

199
00:11:09.200 --> 00:11:12.160
is that if they
withdraw any further.

200
00:11:12.200 --> 00:11:16.840
they will forfeit any possible
material or manpower advantage

201
00:11:16.880 --> 00:11:19.080
over the German armies.

202
00:11:19.120 --> 00:11:23.040
- Both Hitler and Stalin
understand the symbolic power

203
00:11:23.080 --> 00:11:24.320
of Stalingrad.

204
00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.640
- Hitler gets fixated
on Stalingrad. you know?

205
00:11:28.680 --> 00:11:30.880
It bears Stalin's name.

206
00:11:30.920 --> 00:11:32.840
Why don't I take Stalingrad?

207
00:11:32.880 --> 00:11:34.800
And this will be
just a. you know.

208
00:11:34.840 --> 00:11:37.600
an unspeakable humiliation
to Stalin

209
00:11:37.640 --> 00:11:39.560
and it'll be. you know.
a sign of. you know.

210
00:11:39.600 --> 00:11:40.720
of German supremacy.

211
00:11:43.240 --> 00:11:45.080
- Stalin.
he's under no illusions

212
00:11:45.120 --> 00:11:48.440
that if Stalingrad is reached
by the German forces.

213
00:11:48.480 --> 00:11:49.760
this is going to be

214
00:11:49.800 --> 00:11:51.760
an existential battle
of annihilation.

215
00:11:54.280 --> 00:11:58.600
- The German 6th Army
surrounds Stalingrad.

216
00:12:02.680 --> 00:12:05.480
- Stalingrad.
a city of 800.000.

217
00:12:05.520 --> 00:12:09.280
is spread along 30 miles
of the Volga River.

218
00:12:11.280 --> 00:12:14.800
It has modern
apartment blocks.

219
00:12:14.840 --> 00:12:20.120
parks. and heavy
industrial factories.

220
00:12:32.920 --> 00:12:37.520
On August 23. the Luftwaffe
bombardment begins.

221
00:12:46.640 --> 00:12:51.240
In the first 24 hours.
thousands are killed.

222
00:12:54.560 --> 00:12:57.840
Still. Stalin orders
all survivors

223
00:12:57.880 --> 00:13:01.480
to remain in the ravaged city.

224
00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:03.640
- Stalin deliberately makes
no organized attempt

225
00:13:03.680 --> 00:13:07.080
to evacuate
the civilian inhabitants.

226
00:13:07.120 --> 00:13:09.680
Have the Germans
attack. shell. bomb.

227
00:13:09.720 --> 00:13:12.840
He wants to showcase
German barbarism.

228
00:13:12.880 --> 00:13:14.320
But he also figures that

229
00:13:14.360 --> 00:13:16.640
this will stiffen
the resistance of Stalingrad.

230
00:13:19.120 --> 00:13:20.960
- His thinking
at this point is that

231
00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:24.520
if I leave a Russian population
in a city center.

232
00:13:24.560 --> 00:13:26.240
that Soviet soldiers
will fight

233
00:13:26.280 --> 00:13:29.880
all that more heroically
in their defense.

234
00:13:32.320 --> 00:13:34.080
- Stalingrad has
been destroyed.

235
00:13:34.120 --> 00:13:36.400
There is devastation
everywhere.

236
00:13:36.440 --> 00:13:40.440
But the German 6th Army.
1/4 million men. 500 tanks.

237
00:13:40.480 --> 00:13:43.760
is ready to push in the city
and conquer it.

238
00:13:45.680 --> 00:13:50.000
- Germany's 6th Army is led
by General Friedrich Paulus.

239
00:13:52.040 --> 00:13:55.240
- Paulus as a character
is quite weak.

240
00:13:55.280 --> 00:13:57.040
He doesn't have
the self-confidence

241
00:13:57.080 --> 00:14:01.720
of a Manstein or a Rommel
or anybody like that.

242
00:14:01.760 --> 00:14:05.120
- Friedrich Paulus is one
of Hitler's less able generals.

243
00:14:05.160 --> 00:14:08.160
He doesn't have a lot
of experience in battle.

244
00:14:08.200 --> 00:14:10.680
He's a technocrat who's
going to get the job done.

245
00:14:10.720 --> 00:14:12.680
and Hitler doesn't think
the job's going to be

246
00:14:12.720 --> 00:14:14.600
particularly difficult.

247
00:14:19.120 --> 00:14:21.600
- After two weeks
of constant bombardment.

248
00:14:21.640 --> 00:14:24.360
General Paulus orders
the 6th Army

249
00:14:24.400 --> 00:14:26.400
to enter Stalingrad.

250
00:14:30.480 --> 00:14:32.800
There. the German troops
are confronted

251
00:14:32.840 --> 00:14:35.360
with a unique
battered landscape

252
00:14:35.400 --> 00:14:39.080
that provides cover for
thousands of Soviet soldiers.

253
00:14:44.080 --> 00:14:48.000
- Imagine an urban warfare
campaign in New York.

254
00:14:50.840 --> 00:14:53.360
Or London.

255
00:14:53.400 --> 00:14:58.680
It's a partially destroyed.
nightmarish ruin.

256
00:14:58.720 --> 00:15:01.880
There's actually civilians
still running around

257
00:15:01.920 --> 00:15:03.880
and living.
like. in little caves

258
00:15:03.920 --> 00:15:05.360
that they've dug
out of the rubble.

259
00:15:07.600 --> 00:15:10.040
The environment is surreal.

260
00:15:11.800 --> 00:15:15.800
- The Germans describe this
savage close-quarter combat

261
00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:19.280
as Rattenkrieg.
war of the rats.

262
00:15:21.520 --> 00:15:23.440
- The German notion
of Rattenkrieg.

263
00:15:23.480 --> 00:15:25.480
rats scurrying between rubble.

264
00:15:25.520 --> 00:15:28.400
soldiers maneuvering
in and out of sewers.

265
00:15:28.440 --> 00:15:30.400
it's open a door.
there's an enemy.

266
00:15:30.440 --> 00:15:32.760
Now all of a sudden.
you're fighting with fists.

267
00:15:32.800 --> 00:15:35.160
not with artillery
and not with tanks.

268
00:15:35.200 --> 00:15:37.800
It is a very face-to-face.
personal.

269
00:15:37.840 --> 00:15:41.720
and infantry
energy-intensive battle.

270
00:15:43.480 --> 00:15:46.560
- The Germans push through
the mangled industrial debris

271
00:15:46.600 --> 00:15:48.840
of factories and oil depots.

272
00:15:53.760 --> 00:15:55.440
Hiding within the ruins...

273
00:15:56.960 --> 00:16:00.560
Soviet snipers pick off
individual soldiers...

274
00:16:04.280 --> 00:16:07.880
Sowing a sense
of random terror.

275
00:16:09.280 --> 00:16:13.520
The most skilled marksmen
become legends.

276
00:16:13.560 --> 00:16:16.360
Men like Vasiliy Zaytsev.

277
00:16:16.400 --> 00:16:19.320
who becomes a hero
throughout the Soviet Union.

278
00:16:21.120 --> 00:16:25.720
Everyone. young and old.
is expected to fight.

279
00:16:25.760 --> 00:16:27.920
including women.

280
00:16:27.960 --> 00:16:31.080
- Women are very much part
of the Red Army effort anyway.

281
00:16:31.120 --> 00:16:34.360
But in Stalingrad.
they're trapped in the city.

282
00:16:34.400 --> 00:16:35.880
And so they would
just get in there

283
00:16:35.920 --> 00:16:38.680
and start to fight equally
with the men.

284
00:16:38.720 --> 00:16:41.240
They dig tank traps.
they learn how to shoot.

285
00:16:41.280 --> 00:16:42.880
they become snipers.

286
00:16:45.680 --> 00:16:49.200
- But despite the Red Army's
gallant defense of Stalingrad.

287
00:16:49.240 --> 00:16:52.160
street by street.
yard by yard.

288
00:16:52.200 --> 00:16:54.080
the Germans are
gaining ground.

289
00:16:56.040 --> 00:16:57.600
By the second week
of fighting.

290
00:16:57.640 --> 00:17:00.960
the Soviets are in danger
of losing the city.

291
00:17:02.760 --> 00:17:06.319
At the same time.
German forces are closing in

292
00:17:06.359 --> 00:17:08.760
on the oil fields
in the Caucasus.

293
00:17:15.800 --> 00:17:17.680
- The Battle of Stalingrad
is going badly.

294
00:17:17.720 --> 00:17:21.000
The entire Soviet Union seems
to be staring down the barrel.

295
00:17:21.040 --> 00:17:23.800
Stalin decides he has to do
something dramatic

296
00:17:23.839 --> 00:17:25.640
to save the city.

297
00:17:25.680 --> 00:17:29.080
- Stalin summons his first
deputy commander-in-chief.

298
00:17:29.120 --> 00:17:30.800
Georgy Zhukov.

299
00:17:30.840 --> 00:17:34.800
who successfully defended
Leningrad and Moscow.

300
00:17:34.840 --> 00:17:36.520
At a meeting in the Kremlin.

301
00:17:36.560 --> 00:17:41.560
Stalin confers with Zhukov
on military strategy.

302
00:17:41.600 --> 00:17:45.480
- Stalin had always wanted
to be a military commander.

303
00:17:45.520 --> 00:17:47.680
Long before World War II.

304
00:17:47.720 --> 00:17:50.760
he dressed
as a military commander.

305
00:17:50.800 --> 00:17:52.360
But he's not a commander.

306
00:17:52.400 --> 00:17:55.080
he's not a brilliantly
talented strategist.

307
00:17:55.120 --> 00:17:58.760
and he's still constantly
overruling his generals.

308
00:17:58.800 --> 00:18:01.240
ordering offensives
that are unnecessary.

309
00:18:01.280 --> 00:18:03.040
that are unprepared.

310
00:18:03.080 --> 00:18:08.480
But now. Stalin begins to learn
to listen to people he trusts.

311
00:18:08.520 --> 00:18:10.600
- He's starting to find
talented people.

312
00:18:10.640 --> 00:18:14.040
Field Marshal Georgy Zhukov.
who helped defend Moscow.

313
00:18:14.080 --> 00:18:18.240
he's now going. hey. that guy.
I think he knows how to win.

314
00:18:18.280 --> 00:18:23.120
- Zhukov is broad-shouldered.
he's short. he's muscular.

315
00:18:23.160 --> 00:18:25.720
He's an incredibly
tough person.

316
00:18:25.760 --> 00:18:28.080
He literally clears minefields

317
00:18:28.120 --> 00:18:30.840
by sending troops
running across them.

318
00:18:30.880 --> 00:18:33.320
The quintessential
Stalinist general.

319
00:18:35.600 --> 00:18:39.480
- Zhukov presents Stalin
with a new plan:

320
00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:43.440
lure the 6th Army
deeper into Stalingrad.

321
00:18:43.480 --> 00:18:46.160
then surround them
and counterattack

322
00:18:46.200 --> 00:18:48.360
from the rear of the city.

323
00:18:48.400 --> 00:18:50.000
- At the end of the meeting.

324
00:18:50.040 --> 00:18:54.200
Stalin shakes hands for
the first time with Zhukov.

325
00:18:54.240 --> 00:18:56.840
something
he's never done before.

326
00:18:56.880 --> 00:18:59.120
because he realizes that
if this works.

327
00:18:59.160 --> 00:19:01.520
the tide of the war
will change.

328
00:19:12.320 --> 00:19:16.000
- In September 1942.
Soviet General Zhukov

329
00:19:16.040 --> 00:19:19.760
had designed a new strategy
to defend Stalingrad.

330
00:19:19.800 --> 00:19:22.880
Relying largely
on deception.

331
00:19:22.920 --> 00:19:26.280
he opens up misleading
radio channels.

332
00:19:26.320 --> 00:19:28.640
orders fake defenses.

333
00:19:28.680 --> 00:19:33.080
and starts construction
on 17 false bridges.

334
00:19:33.120 --> 00:19:36.160
- The Soviets are starting
to learn the art of war.

335
00:19:36.200 --> 00:19:39.880
This is not the Soviet army
of 1941.

336
00:19:39.920 --> 00:19:42.120
- Zhukov. a chess player.

337
00:19:42.160 --> 00:19:45.560
is known for
meticulous planning.

338
00:19:45.600 --> 00:19:48.160
- Zhukov's plans for
the operation are elaborate.

339
00:19:48.200 --> 00:19:50.440
and they take weeks to prepare.

340
00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:57.400
- The army inside Stalingrad
is completely unaware

341
00:19:57.440 --> 00:19:58.960
of what its real role is.

342
00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:02.000
Its role is to be
the bait in the trap.

343
00:20:02.040 --> 00:20:05.000
Their commander knows that
the only way he can do it

344
00:20:05.040 --> 00:20:07.920
is by sacrificing
more and more men.

345
00:20:13.440 --> 00:20:15.120
- By October.

346
00:20:15.160 --> 00:20:19.280
both armies combined lose
nearly 6.000 troops a day.

347
00:20:22.880 --> 00:20:27.320
And both sides are equally
ruthless in their tactics.

348
00:20:29.120 --> 00:20:32.640
- German soldiers would
bribe these poor orphans

349
00:20:32.680 --> 00:20:34.880
to go and fill their
water bottles in the Volga

350
00:20:34.920 --> 00:20:36.560
with a crust of bread.

351
00:20:36.600 --> 00:20:38.080
Soviet snipers were ordered

352
00:20:38.120 --> 00:20:39.960
to shoot down the Russian
children who were starving.

353
00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:42.920
This was the pitilessness
of the battle.

354
00:20:49.960 --> 00:20:53.120
- At his headquarters.
Adolf Hitler is informed

355
00:20:53.160 --> 00:20:54.560
that his army won't be able

356
00:20:54.600 --> 00:20:58.560
to take the oil fields
in the Caucasus.

357
00:20:58.600 --> 00:21:01.720
His earlier decision
to split his forces

358
00:21:01.760 --> 00:21:03.960
has doomed the operation.

359
00:21:05.280 --> 00:21:07.000
- Hitler is told
that actually.

360
00:21:07.040 --> 00:21:10.680
we haven't got enough troops
to seize the oil fields.

361
00:21:10.720 --> 00:21:13.040
He explodes in rage.

362
00:21:13.080 --> 00:21:14.680
He says he's been lied to.

363
00:21:14.720 --> 00:21:16.400
He blames his generals.

364
00:21:16.440 --> 00:21:18.760
So it completely changes
the atmosphere

365
00:21:18.800 --> 00:21:20.840
at Fuehrer headquarters.

366
00:21:22.560 --> 00:21:27.120
- Hitler shifts his focus
to one goal:

367
00:21:27.160 --> 00:21:29.320
capturing Stalingrad.

368
00:21:31.080 --> 00:21:34.760
By mid-November. it appears
the 6th Army might just do it.

369
00:21:39.240 --> 00:21:40.600
They make their final push

370
00:21:40.640 --> 00:21:44.520
to encircle Soviet troops
on the Volga.

371
00:21:44.560 --> 00:21:45.960
- The Germans are
feeling confident

372
00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:47.760
about the Battle of Stalingrad.

373
00:21:47.800 --> 00:21:50.240
They already hold
90% of the city.

374
00:21:50.280 --> 00:21:53.240
Hitler is getting reports from
his commanders on the site

375
00:21:53.280 --> 00:21:55.400
that the city is about to fall.

376
00:21:57.040 --> 00:22:00.160
- They're starting to fly
swastika flags.

377
00:22:00.200 --> 00:22:01.920
Hitler is boasting
to his buddies

378
00:22:01.960 --> 00:22:04.960
that Stalingrad's
about to be mine.

379
00:22:19.880 --> 00:22:22.320
- Hitler seems confident
that the Wehrmacht

380
00:22:22.360 --> 00:22:24.960
is on the verge of victory.

381
00:22:29.240 --> 00:22:32.280
As fighting continues
around Stalingrad.

382
00:22:32.320 --> 00:22:35.360
the Red Army unleashes
a deafening fusillade

383
00:22:35.400 --> 00:22:38.160
from over 3.000 Soviet
heavy artillery

384
00:22:38.200 --> 00:22:40.280
and Katyusha rockets.

385
00:22:46.760 --> 00:22:51.040
- Katyusha rockets are
one of the great weapons

386
00:22:51.080 --> 00:22:52.440
invented by the Red Army.

387
00:22:52.480 --> 00:22:56.680
They could fire
these terrifying salvos.

388
00:22:56.720 --> 00:22:59.520
The scream is
completely unearthly.

389
00:23:02.280 --> 00:23:03.960
- The 6th Army's flanks

390
00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:08.320
are defended by badly-equipped
Romanian troops.

391
00:23:08.360 --> 00:23:12.800
This is where Zhukov
focuses his attack.

392
00:23:12.840 --> 00:23:14.800
- They were whipped
by their own officers.

393
00:23:14.840 --> 00:23:18.280
They received
virtually no pay at all.

394
00:23:18.320 --> 00:23:21.600
Their morale was rock-bottom.

395
00:23:21.640 --> 00:23:23.200
Why should they die
for Germany?

396
00:23:28.480 --> 00:23:30.600
- The Romanians are
quickly overrun.

397
00:23:35.560 --> 00:23:38.960
Hundreds of thousands
of Red Army soldiers

398
00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:43.760
encircle the 6th Army
in a pincer movement.

399
00:23:43.800 --> 00:23:48.000
On November 22.
Soviet forces link up

400
00:23:48.040 --> 00:23:52.720
in the town of Kalach
on the Don River.

401
00:23:52.760 --> 00:23:55.440
The 6th Army is
now surrounded

402
00:23:55.480 --> 00:23:58.920
and cut off
from its supply lines.

403
00:23:58.960 --> 00:24:03.160
General Paulus is
in a desperate position.

404
00:24:03.200 --> 00:24:04.720
- One of the most
shocking documents

405
00:24:04.760 --> 00:24:07.440
in the German command
of the Second World War

406
00:24:07.480 --> 00:24:10.120
is the memo that
General Paulus writes back

407
00:24:10.160 --> 00:24:10.960
to Fuehrer headquarters.

408
00:24:13.080 --> 00:24:15.120
It opens with two words.

409
00:24:15.160 --> 00:24:20.520
The army is surrounded.

410
00:24:20.560 --> 00:24:23.360
Words that no German commander
ever believed

411
00:24:23.400 --> 00:24:25.920
they would ever have to write.

412
00:24:25.960 --> 00:24:28.880
- Hitler.
when he hears about this.

413
00:24:28.920 --> 00:24:31.000
is absolutely speechless
with rage.

414
00:24:32.840 --> 00:24:34.640
As far as Hitler was
concerned.

415
00:24:34.680 --> 00:24:37.560
the capture of Stalingrad had
been proclaimed as a victory.

416
00:24:37.600 --> 00:24:41.760
It was only a few days before
the great Soviet encirclement.

417
00:24:41.800 --> 00:24:45.920
He could not admit
that they had lost it.

418
00:24:45.960 --> 00:24:47.400
- This crucial battle

419
00:24:47.440 --> 00:24:51.600
has altered Stalin's approach
to leadership.

420
00:24:51.640 --> 00:24:55.160
- Stalin had been
the headstrong. clumsy.

421
00:24:55.200 --> 00:24:57.080
and obstinate commander

422
00:24:57.120 --> 00:25:00.680
who constantly
makes colossal mistakes

423
00:25:00.720 --> 00:25:03.240
with catastrophic effects.

424
00:25:03.280 --> 00:25:08.040
Stalin by now has learned
to listen to generals.

425
00:25:08.080 --> 00:25:10.800
to recognize the limits
of his expertise.

426
00:25:10.840 --> 00:25:12.520
and to let them plan the detail

427
00:25:12.560 --> 00:25:15.320
while he sets
the larger strategy.

428
00:25:16.960 --> 00:25:18.640
- You start to see
this transition

429
00:25:18.680 --> 00:25:20.720
of Joseph Stalin
into political leader

430
00:25:20.760 --> 00:25:23.040
and letting
his military professionals

431
00:25:23.080 --> 00:25:24.320
fight the battles.

432
00:25:24.360 --> 00:25:25.520
Joseph Stalin is indeed

433
00:25:25.560 --> 00:25:27.200
maturing as a war leader.

434
00:25:28.840 --> 00:25:29.840
- Stalin's forces have
Paulus's 6th Army surrounded.

435
00:25:30.320 --> 00:25:33.720
- Stalin's forces have
Paulus's 6th Army surrounded.

436
00:25:33.760 --> 00:25:38.480
The Russian winter
is closing in.

437
00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:44.920
- November 1942.

438
00:25:46.800 --> 00:25:51.680
Winter descends over
the Eastern front.

439
00:25:51.720 --> 00:25:53.960
What remains
of the German 6th Army

440
00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:56.560
is trapped in the city
of Stalingrad.

441
00:25:56.600 --> 00:26:01.840
250.000 men are completely
surrounded by Soviet troops.

442
00:26:05.120 --> 00:26:09.200
General Paulus asks permission
to attempt a breakout.

443
00:26:11.440 --> 00:26:13.440
Hitler refuses.

444
00:26:13.480 --> 00:26:16.000
- Hitler is linked
with the stand fast order.

445
00:26:16.040 --> 00:26:19.200
Where the German soldier
sets foot. there he stays.

446
00:26:19.240 --> 00:26:23.240
Not taking Stalingrad
is not an option.

447
00:26:23.280 --> 00:26:25.560
It has to do
with public opinion.

448
00:26:25.600 --> 00:26:29.640
But Hitler knows the degree
of the predicament he's in.

449
00:26:33.360 --> 00:26:36.600
- The Wehrmacht is now going
to face not only a Soviet army

450
00:26:36.640 --> 00:26:39.800
that is growing in capability.
capacity. and credibility.

451
00:26:39.840 --> 00:26:43.280
they're also going to have
to face the Russian winter.

452
00:26:43.320 --> 00:26:44.920
Soldiers don't have
the right gear.

453
00:26:44.960 --> 00:26:47.600
supplies become harder.
vehicles are harder to start.

454
00:26:47.640 --> 00:26:48.800
maintenance is harder to do.

455
00:26:48.840 --> 00:26:50.200
Everything that should be easy

456
00:26:50.240 --> 00:26:52.600
becomes more difficult
because people are cold.

457
00:26:54.640 --> 00:26:57.160
- How long till
the ammunition runs out?

458
00:26:57.200 --> 00:26:59.400
How long till the medical
supplies run out?

459
00:27:04.640 --> 00:27:07.320
- The Germans are hit
by the full force

460
00:27:07.360 --> 00:27:09.920
of the Russian winter.

461
00:27:09.960 --> 00:27:12.960
- You're talking about
bitterly cold weather.

462
00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:14.520
people suffering
from frostbite.

463
00:27:16.560 --> 00:27:20.200
- People are literally dying
of cold where they stand.

464
00:27:20.240 --> 00:27:22.400
The bodies are frozen solid.

465
00:27:24.720 --> 00:27:28.000
You could break off their arm.
they're so frozen.

466
00:27:29.600 --> 00:27:31.920
- Soldiers are dying
of dysentery.

467
00:27:31.960 --> 00:27:33.720
typhoid. and tuberculosis.

468
00:27:35.680 --> 00:27:38.440
By the end of December.
their daily food intake

469
00:27:38.480 --> 00:27:42.360
is less than a handful of
bread with weak. watery soup.

470
00:27:44.120 --> 00:27:46.640
The troops are starving.

471
00:27:46.680 --> 00:27:48.960
- There are dead men
lying everywhere.

472
00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:50.320
There are rats everywhere.

473
00:27:50.360 --> 00:27:53.160
There's no fuel.
There's nothing to burn.

474
00:27:53.200 --> 00:27:55.760
There's absolutely no thought
of fighting anymore.

475
00:27:55.800 --> 00:27:59.680
Even hanging on to life has
become almost impossible.

476
00:27:59.720 --> 00:28:01.840
- You see German soldiers
and officers

477
00:28:01.880 --> 00:28:05.880
asking the doctors for pills so
that they could commit suicide.

478
00:28:05.920 --> 00:28:08.160
- They are frozen.

479
00:28:08.200 --> 00:28:11.440
They are desperate.

480
00:28:11.480 --> 00:28:13.680
It's a scene of hell on Earth.

481
00:28:18.800 --> 00:28:21.800
- Back in Germany.
the public is largely unaware

482
00:28:21.840 --> 00:28:25.520
of how serious
the situation has become.

483
00:28:27.320 --> 00:28:29.840
But now some are getting
letters from their loved ones

484
00:28:29.880 --> 00:28:32.400
detailing
the horrors unfolding

485
00:28:32.440 --> 00:28:34.760
in the ruins of Stalingrad.

486
00:28:36.680 --> 00:28:38.880
- Try to put yourself
in the place

487
00:28:38.920 --> 00:28:40.880
of these German troops.

488
00:28:40.920 --> 00:28:42.800
You're very far away
from home. right?

489
00:28:42.840 --> 00:28:44.240
It's Christmas season

490
00:28:44.280 --> 00:28:46.040
and you're listening
to the radio

491
00:28:46.080 --> 00:28:47.680
and they're playing
"Silent Night."

492
00:28:47.720 --> 00:28:49.800
At a certain point.
you realize

493
00:28:49.840 --> 00:28:52.280
that they're basically
writing you off.

494
00:28:53.600 --> 00:28:55.000
- Again and again.

495
00:28:55.040 --> 00:28:57.480
Paulus asked for permission
to break out.

496
00:28:59.160 --> 00:29:03.680
Each time.
Hitler's answer is no.

497
00:29:07.040 --> 00:29:08.880
- General Paulus's men
are dying

498
00:29:08.920 --> 00:29:11.080
in the thousands every day.

499
00:29:11.120 --> 00:29:15.520
Any sense of military utility
had long departed.

500
00:29:15.560 --> 00:29:18.760
And yet.
Paulus chose loyalty to Hitler

501
00:29:18.800 --> 00:29:20.960
over loyalty to the men
under his command.

502
00:29:22.600 --> 00:29:24.360
- Hitler has created
a command culture

503
00:29:24.400 --> 00:29:27.160
in which his commanders can't
use their professionalism

504
00:29:27.200 --> 00:29:28.600
and their expertise
on the ground

505
00:29:28.640 --> 00:29:30.400
to do what's best
for their forces.

506
00:29:30.440 --> 00:29:33.640
and so this is also a failure
of Hitler's management

507
00:29:33.680 --> 00:29:35.360
of his commanders.

508
00:29:37.200 --> 00:29:38.720
- By the end of January.

509
00:29:38.760 --> 00:29:42.480
Paulus informs Hitler
that they cannot fight on.

510
00:29:42.520 --> 00:29:44.480
Hitler responds
with a radio message

511
00:29:44.520 --> 00:29:47.560
promoting Paulus
to field marshal

512
00:29:47.600 --> 00:29:51.040
and congratulating him
on his new position.

513
00:29:51.080 --> 00:29:53.160
- Hitler does this not
out of any great love

514
00:29:53.200 --> 00:29:55.400
or admiration from Paulus.

515
00:29:55.440 --> 00:29:57.480
He does it because
no field marshal

516
00:29:57.520 --> 00:30:00.880
has ever surrendered
in the field in German history.

517
00:30:00.920 --> 00:30:03.320
- He feels that
this is one way of basically

518
00:30:03.360 --> 00:30:05.840
making Paulus commit suicide.

519
00:30:10.280 --> 00:30:12.560
- The next day. Paulus goes

520
00:30:12.600 --> 00:30:16.120
to Red Army headquarters
outside Stalingrad.

521
00:30:16.160 --> 00:30:20.040
150.000 of his men are dead.

522
00:30:23.640 --> 00:30:25.800
- Paulus is trapped.

523
00:30:25.840 --> 00:30:28.880
He faces an impossible choice.

524
00:30:28.920 --> 00:30:33.560
- Paulus surrenders
what is left of the 6th Army.

525
00:30:33.600 --> 00:30:36.560
The remaining
90.000 German troops

526
00:30:36.600 --> 00:30:39.240
are led away
as prisoners of war.

527
00:30:39.280 --> 00:30:43.400
Only a small number of them
will ever see Germany again.

528
00:30:45.600 --> 00:30:48.400
- It really was a shock
to the Nazi elite.

529
00:30:48.440 --> 00:30:50.720
but also to the people
of Germany.

530
00:30:50.760 --> 00:30:54.960
Psychologically. it really was
the turning point.

531
00:30:55.000 --> 00:30:57.080
- All of the sudden.
the unthinkable.

532
00:30:57.120 --> 00:30:59.320
the idea that you
might lose this war.

533
00:30:59.360 --> 00:31:01.720
is right there in your face.

534
00:31:01.760 --> 00:31:03.720
And everyone back at home
would have known about it.

535
00:31:03.760 --> 00:31:06.680
The morale is going to suffer.

536
00:31:06.720 --> 00:31:09.360
That's a turn-the-tables
moment.

537
00:31:11.280 --> 00:31:13.680
- There's very few families
in Germany that didn't have

538
00:31:13.720 --> 00:31:15.520
some tie to the 6th Army--

539
00:31:15.560 --> 00:31:18.680
a son. a father.
a neighbor's son.

540
00:31:18.720 --> 00:31:20.320
The 6th Army was
the largest army

541
00:31:20.360 --> 00:31:21.760
in the German order of battle.

542
00:31:21.800 --> 00:31:23.960
and now it's been
completely destroyed.

543
00:31:26.640 --> 00:31:27.920
- When Hitler receives
the news

544
00:31:27.960 --> 00:31:29.160
of Paulus's surrender.

545
00:31:29.200 --> 00:31:31.280
he's silent for several hours.

546
00:31:32.600 --> 00:31:34.840
Then he explodes.

547
00:31:34.880 --> 00:31:36.200
- He actually says.

548
00:31:36.240 --> 00:31:38.920
why didn't Paulus
put a bullet in his brain?

549
00:31:38.960 --> 00:31:40.320
It only takes a second.

550
00:31:40.360 --> 00:31:43.080
and he would have been immortal
from then on.

551
00:31:43.120 --> 00:31:44.520
But instead. he chose

552
00:31:44.560 --> 00:31:48.640
what Hitler said was
the coward's way out.

553
00:31:48.680 --> 00:31:52.360
But Hitler knows
the gravity of this defeat.

554
00:31:54.640 --> 00:31:59.600
- To lose 250.000 men
in a moment. essentially.

555
00:31:59.640 --> 00:32:02.480
in other words.
to have that military force

556
00:32:02.520 --> 00:32:04.320
wiped off your ledger.

557
00:32:04.360 --> 00:32:07.680
that hadn't happened
to the Germans in the war.

558
00:32:07.720 --> 00:32:10.800
It changes the political
calculation entirely.

559
00:32:10.840 --> 00:32:13.720
and this myth of invincibility
is going to be shattered.

560
00:32:16.640 --> 00:32:19.000
- In a single campaign.
Hitler has lost an army

561
00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:21.240
- In a single campaign.
Hitler has lost an army

562
00:32:21.280 --> 00:32:26.520
and began to lose the faith
of the German people.

563
00:32:37.120 --> 00:32:39.320
- Following the defeat
of Stalingrad.

564
00:32:39.360 --> 00:32:44.760
Adolf Hitler withdraws to his
mountain retreat in Bavaria.

565
00:32:44.800 --> 00:32:48.480
On April 20. 1943.
his inner circle

566
00:32:48.520 --> 00:32:52.040
throws a party to mark
his 54th birthday.

567
00:32:55.360 --> 00:32:56.920
- After Stalingrad.

568
00:32:56.960 --> 00:32:59.960
all the indicators are
running against Germany.

569
00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:03.720
The campaign in North Africa
has clearly gone bad.

570
00:33:03.760 --> 00:33:07.720
Increasingly. Hitler is
losing control of himself.

571
00:33:07.760 --> 00:33:10.960
The entire 1942 campaign
had been marked

572
00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:15.040
by gigantic tantrums
against his officers.

573
00:33:15.080 --> 00:33:17.520
He is no longer
up to the stress

574
00:33:17.560 --> 00:33:19.520
of running a global war.

575
00:33:19.560 --> 00:33:20.920
But Hitler knows

576
00:33:20.960 --> 00:33:24.720
that he has to launch
an offensive in 1943

577
00:33:24.760 --> 00:33:29.160
or he risks losing control
of the war completely.

578
00:33:29.200 --> 00:33:32.200
- The Germans have
enough armor

579
00:33:32.240 --> 00:33:34.320
and enough energy
and enough manpower

580
00:33:34.360 --> 00:33:37.920
to mount one final offensive
on the Eastern Front.

581
00:33:39.040 --> 00:33:42.600
- The Soviets have advanced
into an area to the south.

582
00:33:42.640 --> 00:33:43.920
creating a salient

583
00:33:43.960 --> 00:33:46.560
around a region called Kursk.

584
00:33:48.240 --> 00:33:53.560
Hitler sees an opportunity
to seize the initiative.

585
00:33:53.600 --> 00:33:56.600
- The salient around Kursk
in 1943

586
00:33:56.640 --> 00:33:58.960
was such an obvious target
that basically.

587
00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:03.280
both sides knew some type
of offensive was coming.

588
00:34:03.320 --> 00:34:08.320
- Hitler is basically putting
all of his chips on the table.

589
00:34:08.360 --> 00:34:10.960
- But his resources
are already stretched

590
00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:12.360
across Europe.

591
00:34:15.679 --> 00:34:18.040
- Everything is getting harder
by 1943.

592
00:34:18.080 --> 00:34:19.840
The Soviet artillery
is better.

593
00:34:19.880 --> 00:34:22.560
their tanks are better.
their leadership is better.

594
00:34:22.600 --> 00:34:24.679
So it will take
a lot of resources.

595
00:34:24.719 --> 00:34:25.880
it'll take a lot of armor.

596
00:34:25.920 --> 00:34:27.760
and it will cost
in order to do this.

597
00:34:29.800 --> 00:34:33.120
- Considering the resources
of Nazi Germany at this point.

598
00:34:33.159 --> 00:34:35.480
its economic reserves.
its soldiers.

599
00:34:35.520 --> 00:34:40.239
this is a ridiculous thing
to attempt.

600
00:34:40.280 --> 00:34:43.239
- Hitler is particularly
excited about his giant tanks.

601
00:34:43.280 --> 00:34:44.760
the Tigers and Panthers.

602
00:34:44.800 --> 00:34:46.520
which he thinks are
game-changers.

603
00:34:49.719 --> 00:34:51.280
- In Moscow.

604
00:34:51.320 --> 00:34:54.120
the Soviet High Command
is receiving intelligence

605
00:34:54.159 --> 00:34:56.760
about the Germans'
upcoming offensive.

606
00:34:58.680 --> 00:35:00.480
Unlike earlier in the war.

607
00:35:00.520 --> 00:35:05.320
Stalin is now utilizing
the intelligence he receives.

608
00:35:05.360 --> 00:35:07.480
- Stalin's instincts are
always just attack now.

609
00:35:07.520 --> 00:35:10.600
attack on all fronts.
attack at any cost.

610
00:35:10.640 --> 00:35:13.480
By the time of Kursk.
he's learned that actually.

611
00:35:13.520 --> 00:35:15.520
this is not the way
to win a war.

612
00:35:15.560 --> 00:35:18.880
Now he's taking
the intelligence on board.

613
00:35:18.920 --> 00:35:20.160
He's trusting it.

614
00:35:20.200 --> 00:35:22.440
The German attack
is going to be massive.

615
00:35:22.480 --> 00:35:25.840
Zhukov persuades Stalin.
we're going to dig in.

616
00:35:25.880 --> 00:35:27.200
we're going to prepare.

617
00:35:27.240 --> 00:35:29.160
and we're going
to draw the Germans in.

618
00:35:31.360 --> 00:35:34.360
- As Zhukov prepares
for the coming offensive.

619
00:35:34.400 --> 00:35:38.000
Soviet factories
increase their production.

620
00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:43.480
- By this stage of the war.
the Soviet economy

621
00:35:43.520 --> 00:35:48.160
is vastly outproducing
the German economy.

622
00:35:48.200 --> 00:35:52.720
Stalin was now producing
massive amounts of weaponry.

623
00:35:52.760 --> 00:35:56.080
- The United States has also
been sending military supplies

624
00:35:56.120 --> 00:35:59.400
to the Soviets through
its Lend-Lease plan.

625
00:35:59.440 --> 00:36:01.760
which was designed
to get American materials

626
00:36:01.800 --> 00:36:04.920
to Great Britain
and the Soviet Union.

627
00:36:04.960 --> 00:36:08.120
By 1943.
tons of military hardware

628
00:36:08.160 --> 00:36:11.040
are rolling off Allied ships
each month.

629
00:36:13.560 --> 00:36:15.560
- The Soviets were
especially impressed

630
00:36:15.600 --> 00:36:19.920
with the Willys Jeeps.
the American Sherman tanks.

631
00:36:19.960 --> 00:36:23.480
along with
more than 12.000 warplanes.

632
00:36:27.920 --> 00:36:29.520
- The Soviets are
also receiving

633
00:36:29.560 --> 00:36:32.200
hundreds of thousands
of tons of food.

634
00:36:35.840 --> 00:36:38.680
- The Soviet army
is actually being fed

635
00:36:38.720 --> 00:36:41.520
by the American economy
in 1943.

636
00:36:41.560 --> 00:36:44.640
everything from
the famous tushonka pork

637
00:36:44.680 --> 00:36:46.160
Americans refer to as Spam

638
00:36:46.200 --> 00:36:50.880
to millions of packets
of dehydrated borscht.

639
00:36:50.920 --> 00:36:54.120
- One of the ways that Hitler
wants to defeat these people

640
00:36:54.160 --> 00:36:56.680
and whittle down their numbers
is through starvation.

641
00:36:56.720 --> 00:36:58.800
But if they're being fed
from outside sources.

642
00:36:58.840 --> 00:37:00.120
you can't do that.

643
00:37:02.400 --> 00:37:04.280
- The supplies help
the Soviets build

644
00:37:04.320 --> 00:37:07.840
one of the largest
defensive forces ever seen.

645
00:37:07.880 --> 00:37:10.600
1.3 million troops.

646
00:37:13.400 --> 00:37:14.880
At Zhukov's command.

647
00:37:14.920 --> 00:37:17.760
civilians dig several thousand
miles of trenches

648
00:37:17.800 --> 00:37:22.280
and tank traps outside Kursk.

649
00:37:22.320 --> 00:37:26.440
Nearly one million mines
are laid.

650
00:37:26.480 --> 00:37:29.320
- It's the most
densely defended area

651
00:37:29.360 --> 00:37:30.720
of the whole Earth

652
00:37:30.760 --> 00:37:32.720
in the course
of the Second World War.

653
00:37:37.840 --> 00:37:38.560
- The Soviets are prepared

654
00:37:38.720 --> 00:37:40.240
- The Soviets are prepared

655
00:37:40.280 --> 00:37:44.520
for the full weight
of the German Wehrmacht.

656
00:37:52.920 --> 00:37:55.320
- July 1943.

657
00:37:57.760 --> 00:37:59.760
The Germans launch
their colossal offensive

658
00:37:59.800 --> 00:38:02.800
against the Red Army
in the Kursk salient.

659
00:38:08.440 --> 00:38:10.360
Quickly. the German advance

660
00:38:10.400 --> 00:38:13.240
runs into
Zhukov's fortifications.

661
00:38:18.560 --> 00:38:22.120
- It's the countermove
to the idea of blitzkrieg.

662
00:38:23.640 --> 00:38:25.280
If you break through
the front line.

663
00:38:25.320 --> 00:38:26.960
there's another line
behind there

664
00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:30.320
with antitank efforts
and trenches and men.

665
00:38:30.360 --> 00:38:32.520
If you break through that one.
there's another one.

666
00:38:39.640 --> 00:38:41.640
Your forces
as the German Wehrmacht

667
00:38:41.680 --> 00:38:44.240
are getting smaller
and weaker and damaged.

668
00:38:44.280 --> 00:38:46.560
And eventually.
you just sort of

669
00:38:46.600 --> 00:38:49.440
whittle away
the spear point here.

670
00:38:49.480 --> 00:38:53.680
- For eight days. the Germans
grind against Soviet defenses.

671
00:38:59.320 --> 00:39:02.840
Two vast tank armies collide.

672
00:39:13.120 --> 00:39:15.680
- Astonishing intensity.

673
00:39:18.040 --> 00:39:21.960
Tanks helm-to-helm.
hull-to-hull.

674
00:39:28.840 --> 00:39:31.040
- The German tanks are
better built.

675
00:39:31.080 --> 00:39:33.080
have bigger guns. better armor.

676
00:39:33.120 --> 00:39:34.720
But if you've only got
a few of them

677
00:39:34.760 --> 00:39:38.280
and you've got a mass
of T-34s coming at you.

678
00:39:38.320 --> 00:39:39.440
you have a big problem.

679
00:39:41.080 --> 00:39:42.600
- Hitler's miracle weapons.

680
00:39:42.640 --> 00:39:44.160
the Tigers and Panthers.

681
00:39:44.200 --> 00:39:48.040
which are these giant.
diabolical metal machines.

682
00:39:48.080 --> 00:39:49.920
actually don't work too well.

683
00:39:54.440 --> 00:39:55.960
- Hitler's tanks are destroyed

684
00:39:56.000 --> 00:39:59.280
by the more maneuverable
Soviet tanks.

685
00:40:01.440 --> 00:40:06.240
After two days. the Wehrmacht
is forced to withdraw.

686
00:40:06.280 --> 00:40:07.840
- Hitler has failed.

687
00:40:07.880 --> 00:40:11.360
He's rolled the dice three
times inside the Soviet Union.

688
00:40:11.400 --> 00:40:16.160
Operation Barbarossa in '41.
Operation Blue in '42.

689
00:40:16.200 --> 00:40:18.400
and now.
the great offensive at Kursk.

690
00:40:18.440 --> 00:40:21.200
and he's failed each time.

691
00:40:21.240 --> 00:40:23.840
Hitler's final gamble
on the Eastern Front

692
00:40:23.880 --> 00:40:25.080
has been crushed.

693
00:40:27.280 --> 00:40:29.120
- They get nothing out
of the Battle of Kursk.

694
00:40:29.160 --> 00:40:30.760
It's a huge defeat
for the Germans.

695
00:40:30.800 --> 00:40:32.560
They're always going
to be going backwards

696
00:40:32.600 --> 00:40:34.040
from this point on.

697
00:40:35.160 --> 00:40:37.600
- Kursk destroys enough
of the German combat power

698
00:40:37.640 --> 00:40:38.880
that they can never
take the offensive

699
00:40:38.920 --> 00:40:39.920
for the rest of the war.

700
00:40:39.960 --> 00:40:41.680
Therefore. the Soviets maintain

701
00:40:41.720 --> 00:40:43.920
the initiative to pick the time
and place of the choosing

702
00:40:43.960 --> 00:40:47.080
where they're going
to take their next act.

703
00:40:47.120 --> 00:40:50.040
- This is a decisive moment
in Stalin's development

704
00:40:50.080 --> 00:40:51.960
as a supreme commander.

705
00:40:52.000 --> 00:40:57.600
Hitler is undergoing precisely
the opposite transformation.

706
00:40:57.640 --> 00:40:58.920
- By this point in the war.

707
00:40:58.960 --> 00:41:01.880
Hitler is really
losing his grip on reality.

708
00:41:01.920 --> 00:41:06.520
And people thought he made
some madcap moves in 1940.

709
00:41:06.560 --> 00:41:08.240
but they paid off.

710
00:41:08.280 --> 00:41:09.920
As the war lengthens.

711
00:41:09.960 --> 00:41:13.720
his decisions become
more and more suspect.

712
00:41:13.760 --> 00:41:15.440
- The two great warlords
of World War II

713
00:41:15.480 --> 00:41:20.240
are passing each other as one
develops and one deteriorates.

714
00:41:28.480 --> 00:41:31.840
- In November 1943.
Joseph Stalin meets

715
00:41:31.880 --> 00:41:33.880
with Prime Minister
Winston Churchill

716
00:41:33.920 --> 00:41:36.760
and President
Franklin D. Roosevelt.

717
00:41:39.720 --> 00:41:41.480
It's the first meeting
of the group

718
00:41:41.520 --> 00:41:45.080
that would become known
as The Big Three.

719
00:41:50.120 --> 00:41:52.720
- The Big Three sat down
in Tehran.

720
00:41:52.760 --> 00:41:54.960
around the table
with their teams.

721
00:41:55.000 --> 00:41:59.240
Each of them said something.
and Stalin really put it best.

722
00:41:59.280 --> 00:42:02.800
He said.
history has spoiled us.

723
00:42:02.840 --> 00:42:07.840
Never have three men had
the vast and massive powers

724
00:42:07.880 --> 00:42:09.960
that we have today.

725
00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:11.920
Let's get to work.

726
00:42:16.800 --> 00:42:18.840
- Stalingrad creates
a tradition

727
00:42:18.880 --> 00:42:22.400
that eventually spreads
to the rest of the Red Army.

728
00:42:22.440 --> 00:42:25.040
Soviet soldiers passing
each other in the street

729
00:42:25.080 --> 00:42:29.320
say blind swap. and exchange
the items in their pockets

730
00:42:29.360 --> 00:42:30.720
without looking.

731
00:42:30.760 --> 00:42:33.640
Soldiers swap a single
cigarette for a watch

732
00:42:33.680 --> 00:42:36.520
or money or a scrap of paper.

733
00:42:36.560 --> 00:42:39.200
In Stalingrad.
life is so uncertain.

734
00:42:39.240 --> 00:42:41.200
soldiers could be dead
in an instant.

735
00:42:41.240 --> 00:42:44.440
that nothing has
any value at all.

736
00:42:44.480 --> 00:42:48.080
The battle for Stalingrad is
the turning point of the war

737
00:42:48.120 --> 00:42:49.920
on the Eastern Front.

738
00:42:49.960 --> 00:42:54.600
Never again would the Wehrmacht
take the offensive in the East.

739
00:42:54.640 --> 00:42:56.240
And in the West.

740
00:42:56.280 --> 00:42:59.760
the Allies prepare
to cross the Mediterranean.

741
00:42:59.800 --> 00:43:04.200
the next step in their attack
against the Third Reich.
